The '''citrus gummy bark viroid''' (abbreviated CGBVd) is a sub-species of the [[hop stunt viroid]], and thus is a member of the genus [[Hostuviroid]].

As the name suggests, the citrus gummy bark viroid causes problems in the bark of the [[sweet orange]] tree.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Sofy | first1 = A.R. | last2 = Soliman | first2 = A.M. | last3 = Mousa | first3 = A.A. | last4 = Ghazal | first4 = S.A. | last5 = El-Dougdoug | first5 = K.A. | title = First record of ''Citrus viroid II'' (CVd-II) associated with gummy bark disease in sweet orange (''Citrus sinensis'') in Egypt | journal = New Disease Reports | volume = 21 | pages = 24 | year = 2010 | doi = 10.5197/j.2044-0588.2010.021.024}}</ref>

Scrapping the bark exposes localized spots or a line of reddish-brown, gum-impregnated tissue around the scion circumference especially visible near the bud union. The discoloration and gumming may extend above the bud union to the main branches of the sweet orange while in severe infection dark streaks of gum-impregnated tissue may also be observed in longitudinal sections.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Onelge|first=N.|last2=Cinar|first2=A.|last3=Szychowski|first3=J.A.|last4=Vidalakis|first4=G.|last5=Semancik|first5=J.S.|date=2004|title=Citrus viroid II variants associated with 'Gummy Bark' disease|url=|journal=European Journal of Plant Pathology|volume=110|issue=10|pages=1047–1052|doi=10.1007/s10658-004-0815-2|issn=0929-1873|via=ISI Web of Science}}</ref>

