{{Infobox spaceflight | name = S-45A | image = S-45 1.jpg | image_caption = An S-45 satellite before launch
| mission_type = Ionospheric | operator = [[NASA]] | website = | COSPAR_ID = | SATCAT = | mission_duration = Failed to orbit
| spacecraft_bus = | manufacturer = | dry_mass = | launch_mass = {{convert|33.6|kg}} | power =
| launch_date = {{start-date|24 May 1961, 19:48:05|timezone=yes}}&nbsp;UTC | launch_rocket = [[Juno II]] AM-19G | launch_site = [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]] [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Launch Complex 26|LC-26B]] | launch_contractor =
| disposal_type = | deactivated = | last_contact = <!-- {{end-date|[insert date here]}} --> | decay_date =
| orbit_epoch = | orbit_reference = [[geocentric orbit|Geocentric]] | orbit_regime = [[Highly elliptical orbit|Highly elliptical]] (planned) | orbit_periapsis = | orbit_apoapsis = | orbit_inclination = | orbit_period = | apsis = gee
| programme = ''[[Explorers program|Explorers]]'' | previous_mission = [[Explorer 11]] | next_mission = [[S-55 (satellite)|S-55]] }} '''S-45A''' was an [[United States|American]] [[satellite]], which was lost in a launch failure in 1961. The satellite was intended to operate in a [[highly elliptical orbit]], from which it was to have provided data on the shape of the ionosphere,<ref name="NSSDC">{{cite web|url=http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/masterCatalog.do?sc=EXS-452|title=Explorer S45A|publisher=[[NASA]]|work=NSSDC Master Catalog|accessdate=14 July 2010}}</ref> and on the [[Earth's magnetic field]].<ref name="EA">{{cite web|url=http://www.astronautix.com/craft/p14.htm|title=P-14|first=Mark|last=Wade|publisher=[[Encyclopedia Astronautica]]|accessdate=14 July 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613075713/http://www.astronautix.com/craft/p14.htm|archivedate=13 June 2010|df=}}</ref> It was part of the [[Explorer program]]me, and would have been designated Explorer 12 had it reached orbit. It was the second of two identical satellites to be launched; the first, [[S-45 (satellite)|S-45]], had also been lost in a launch failure, earlier in the year.<ref name="EA"/>
S-45A was launched aboard a [[Juno II]] rocket, serial number AM-19G. It was the final flight of the Juno II.<ref name="LaunchLog"/> The launch took place from [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Launch Complex 26|Launch Complex 26B]] at the [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station]] at 19:48:05 UTC on 24 May 1961.<ref name="LaunchLog">{{cite web|url=http://planet4589.org/space/log/launchlog.txt|title=Launch Log|first=Jonathan|last=McDowell|publisher=Jonathan's Space Page|accessdate=14 July 2010}}</ref> The system which was intended to ignite the second stage malfunctioned, and as a result that stage failed to ignite.<ref name="GSP">{{cite web|url=http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_sdat/explorer_s45.htm|title=Explorer: S-45|first=Gunter|last=Krebs|publisher=Gunter's Space Page|accessdate=14 July 2010}}</ref> The rocket failed to achieve orbit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://msl.jpl.nasa.gov/Programs/explorer.html|title=Explorer Program|work=Mission and Spacecraft Library|publisher=NASA|accessdate=14 July 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080127144116/http://msl.jpl.nasa.gov/Programs/explorer.html|archivedate=27 January 2008|df=}}</ref>
