{{Infobox person |name = William Matthew Hart |image = |caption = |birth_date = 1830 <!-- {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> |birth_place = Walworth, London, England |death_date = 1908 <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> |death_place = Camberwell, London |other_names = |known_for = |occupation = Illustrator and lithographer |nationality = English }} '''William Matthew Hart''' (1830-1908) was an English bird illustrator and lithographer who worked for [[John Gould]].
Hart started medical training, but was unable to complete his studies for financial reasons. He began working for Gould in 1851, beginning an association that was to last thirty years. Early during this period he made the patterns for the [[lithography|lithographic]] plates for Gould’s work on [[hummingbirds]], as well as working on ''The Birds of Great Britain'' with [[Henry Constantine Richter]]. By 1870 Hart had become Gould's chief artist and lithographer. After Gould's death in 1881, Hart was employed by [[Richard Bowdler-Sharpe]] of the [[British Museum]] to complete Gould's work on the birds of New Guinea and to produce illustrations for Sharpe’s monograph on the [[birds-of-paradise]].
==References== {{reflist}} * {{cite book |title= Feather and brush: three centuries of Australian bird art |author=Olsen, Penny |year=2001 |publisher=CSIRO Publishing |location=Melbourne |isbn= 978-0-643-06547-5 |pages= |url= }} * {{cite web |url=http://australianmuseum.net.au/William-Matthew-Hart-1830-1908 |title= William Matthew Hart (1830-1908) |accessdate=2010-08-01 |work= |publisher=Australian Museum |date= }}
